d to us and the wildlife, resulting in permanent hearing loss in humans or survival difficulty in animals, as written above. The serious injuries that are caused to terrestrial and aquatic life are a matter of concern and should be looked upon very carefully. Certain measures could be taken by us to prevent noise pollution and protect ourselves. They include: Switching the appliances off when not in use. Using earplugs. Keeping the volume low. Planting trees often. Regularly maintaining our vehicles and machines. Turning the appliances off We can switch off the appliances at our home or work when they are not being used by anyone. For example, we can turn the TV off when no one is watching it, and gaming systems can be turned off after a little use; computers can be shut down when they aren't being used by anyone. These appliances create unwanted and unnecessary stress on our ears and lead to various health issues. Don't let noise leave the door We can avoid keeping the door open when using noisy appliances such as washing machines and dishwashers. We can close the door before switching them on so that harsh noises such as that of grinders and washers do not directly reach us and harm our ears. Another way of performing these safety measures is by constructing noisy work areas in such a way that their noise doesn't travel out of the rooms. Installation of a sound barrier might also help. Using earplugs Using things like earplugs or earmuffs can be of great benefit to our ears as they cancel out the harsh noise that comes to our ears. Earplugs cover the insides of our ears and lower the sound intensity, and earmuffs cover the whole of our ear, stopping Noise from reaching our ears. Such hearing protections play a vital role in preventing our ears from noise pollution. Workers working under conditions in which they are exposed to 80 decibels should be provided with hearing protection, and people who are exposed to Noise of intensity 85 decibels or more should wear hearing protection daily. Reducing the volume When we are listening to music on our mobile phones or radios or watching television, we can prevent noise pollution by lowing the volume, be it on speaker or on our headphones, to avoid noise from harming us. Social distancing from noise This precaution is something that should be taken not only by us but by the government as well. Building things such as airports, industries, and railway tracks away from the residential areas may provide help in reducing health hazards due to noise to a large number of people. As people, we should have our houses away from noisy places. Limits of noise The government should take measures by creating laws that check the intensity of noise in our neighbourhood, such as loudspeakers, public gatherings and public announcements by politicians. Keeping noise in check can help in reducing it. Sensitive areas Strict control should be acquired over the noise levels in sensitive areas such as schools, hospitals, old age homes etc. Sign boards indicating noise levels should be installed in the corners of sensitive areas. Plants as a solution Trees are considered to be very efficient noise absorbents. In order to reduce noise pollution, we can plant more and more trees by conducting plantation drives as plants have the ability to reduce the Noise around them by 5 to 10 decibels. Good Noise could save the day When there are too many unwanted noises that we cannot kill, then there is something creative we can do to avoid the problem of noise pollution, and that is by creating healthier Noise such as that of music, hummingbirds, water fountains in offices and homes. Using noise absorbers Noise absorbers can be a very useful measure that can be taken in order to reduce harsh noises that comes out from wearing out parts of old machinery. We can get our machines checked and install silencers and vibration dampers inside our machines and tools to prevent them from making Noise. Lubrication of our tools and 