ier, industrialization results in a great increase in sound or noise pollution and the reason for the same is the continuous use of heavy machinery, for example, large exhaust fans, huge generators, and mills, which have been utilized, giving rise to noise pollution. 2. Vehicles Urbanization has led to an increased number of vehicles running on the complex road webs causing noise pollution and making it hard for humans or animals to stand that sound. 3. Events In addition to all this, public events do play their role in giving rise to noise pollution. Be it Weddings, birthdays, public gatherings or any other event whatsoever, they all involve loudspeakers for playing music which results in producing unwanted Noise in the surrounding, which falls under the category of neighbourhood noise. Effects of Noise Pollution on Human Health We all know that noise pollution can be very hazardous to human beings. Here are some details about Noise affects human health. 1. Hypertension Hypertension is caused by the elevation of blood levels for a long period of time, and noise pollution is the rooting cause of hypertension. This condition, if not dealt with care, can further lead to more complex situations like heart diseases and stroke. 2. Hearing loss Hearing impairment is one of the most obvious results of noise pollution. When humans are exposed to sound that is higher than the intensity that our ears have a habit of enduring, it damages the eardrums and, if not dealt with carefully, eventually leads to loss of hearing of a person. 3. Sleeping disorders Lack of sleep leads to many things, including fatigue and having a low energy level throughout the day, which eventually hinders everyday activities in a person's life. Noise pollution leads to a bad sleep cycle which eventually causes irritation and an uncomfortable mental state. People with sleeping disorders might also face mental health problems. 4. Cardiovascular issues Just as mentioned above, a person surrounded by noise pollution suffers from hypertension, and if not treated, it might result in permanent cardiovascular problems. There are many heart-related problems faced by the people, such as blood pressure levels, cardiovascular diseases and stress that might as well develop in a normal person, and if there is a person who is already suffering from any of these diseases might as well have his/her condition worsened. Sound Unit The unit in which sound is measured is called decibels (dB). Different types of sound that are present in the environment have different intensity; for example, the sound of rustling leaves have an intensity of 20 to 30 decibels, a thunderclap has 120 decibels, and the wail of a siren has 120 to 140 decibels. Sounds that have an intensity of 85 decibels or higher have the capability of harming a person's ear. There are many types of sources through which sounds of this intensity are emitted, for example, subway trains (90 to 115 decibels), power lawn mowers (90 decibels), and loud rock concerts (110 to 120 decibels). Impacts of Noise Pollution 1. On Humans Noise pollution causes a serious impact on a number of people daily. Noise Induced Hearing Loss or NIHL is the most common problem caused by noise pollution. Exposing ourselves to high noises can cause serious problems, including high blood pressure, stress, heart diseases, hypertension and sleep disturbance. The thing which makes noise pollution more hazardous is that such kind of noise problem not only affects elder people but its impact can also be seen on every age group, especially children. Children who have their houses close to noisy airports, streets and busy roads are reported to be suffering from problems such as stress, lack of attention to things, poor reading skills, insomnia and so on. 2. On Terrestrial Animals It is not only the human population that is affected by this invincible problem that is Noise pollution, but it also has its dangerous impacts on the health and well-being of wild 