ing a low energy level throughout the day, which eventually hinders everyday activities in a person's life. Noise pollution leads to a bad sleep cycle which eventually causes irritation and an uncomfortable mental state. People with sleeping disorders might also face mental health problems. 4. Cardiovascular issues Just as mentioned above, a person surrounded by noise pollution suffers from hypertension, and if not treated, it might result in permanent cardiovascular problems. There are many heart-related problems faced by the people, such as blood pressure levels, cardiovascular diseases and stress that might as well develop in a normal person, and if there is a person who is already suffering from any of these diseases might as well have his/her condition worsened. Sound Unit The unit in which sound is measured is called decibels (dB). Different types of sound that are present in the environment have different intensity; for example, the sound of rustling leaves have an intensity of 20 to 30 decibels, a thunderclap has 120 decibels, and the wail of a siren has 120 to 140 decibels. Sounds that have an intensity of 85 decibels or higher have the capability of harming a person's ear. There are many types of sources through which sounds of this intensity are emitted, for example, subway trains (90 to 115 decibels), power lawn mowers (90 decibels), and loud rock concerts (110 to 120 decibels). Impacts of Noise Pollution 1. On Humans Noise pollution causes a serious impact on a number of people daily. Noise Induced Hearing Loss or NIHL is the most common problem caused by noise pollution. Exposing ourselves to high noises can cause serious problems, including high blood pressure, stress, heart diseases, hypertension and sleep disturbance. The thing which makes noise pollution more hazardous is that such kind of noise problem not only affects elder people but its impact can also be seen on every age group, especially children. Children who have their houses close to nois